00:00:22.680 --> 00:00:25.520
Let's get started.

00:00:25.520 --> 00:00:27.160
Going to go right
into the lesson.

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:31.020
Last day we started looking
at kinetics, which was the

00:00:31.020 --> 00:00:32.300
description of rate and

00:00:32.300 --> 00:00:35.550
mechanism of chemical reactions.

00:00:35.550 --> 00:00:38.640
We looked at the general rate
law, which shows us that the

00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:42.570
instant change in concentration
of species i

00:00:42.570 --> 00:00:45.740
goes as the instant
concentration.

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:48.550
So rate is proportional
to concentration.

00:00:48.550 --> 00:00:54.360
And the order of reaction
is shown here as n and

00:00:54.360 --> 00:00:57.710
proportionality constant
is the rate constant k.

00:00:57.710 --> 00:01:02.150
So we saw that we can make the
rate of reaction increase by

00:01:02.150 --> 00:01:04.720
increasing the concentration
in the reactor.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:06.940
We saw there was a second way
to increase the rate of

00:01:06.940 --> 00:01:09.390
reaction, and that was to
raise the temperature.

00:01:09.390 --> 00:01:12.800
And this is the Arrhenius
relationship that shows that

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:16.350
the rate constant changes with
temperature according to this

00:01:16.350 --> 00:01:19.020
exponential relationship.

00:01:19.020 --> 00:01:21.500
In the denominator, we have the
product of the Boltzmann

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:24.370
constant and the absolute
temperature, which is a

00:01:24.370 --> 00:01:27.840
measure of the ambient thermal
energy that's available to

00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:29.250
promote reaction.

00:01:29.250 --> 00:01:32.940
And in the numerator we have a
barrier energy, which we call

00:01:32.940 --> 00:01:34.810
the activation energy.

00:01:34.810 --> 00:01:37.130
We'll say a little bit more
about that today.

00:01:37.130 --> 00:01:40.080
And the constant of
proportionality out here is A,

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:42.800
which is in honor of Arrhenius,
who first

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:44.970
annunciated the law.

00:01:44.970 --> 00:01:48.210
So what I want to do today is to
look at some common orders

00:01:48.210 --> 00:01:48.685
of reactions.

00:01:48.685 --> 00:01:52.110
So we're going to look at
the values of n that are

00:01:52.110 --> 00:01:54.990
encountered in not

00:01:54.990 --> 00:01:59.000
insignificant number of reactions.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:00.680
So let's start with
the simplest one.

00:02:00.680 --> 00:02:03.850
The simplest one
is first order.

00:02:03.850 --> 00:02:05.100
First order reactions.

00:02:07.850 --> 00:02:12.570
That means n equals 1 in this
rate law expression.

00:02:12.570 --> 00:02:17.840
And here's an example of
something that we could use.

00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:24.230
The decomposition of
N2O5 into NO2.

00:02:24.230 --> 00:02:30.970
And gives us half a
mole of oxygen.

00:02:30.970 --> 00:02:35.400
And we can write this rate law
in terms of the rate of

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:37.650
disappearance of N2O5.

00:02:37.650 --> 00:02:41.040
So I can write minus
d by dt of--

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:43.680
I'm going to use square brackets
to indicate the

00:02:43.680 --> 00:02:44.592
concentration--

00:02:44.592 --> 00:02:47.030
of N2O5.

00:02:47.030 --> 00:02:48.830
And this has been measured.

00:02:48.830 --> 00:02:50.450
You can't predict this from the

00:02:50.450 --> 00:02:52.520
stoichiometry of the equation.

00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:55.410
You have to measure this, and
on the basis of measurements

00:02:55.410 --> 00:03:02.780
it's found that the rate of
change of N2O5 goes as the

00:03:02.780 --> 00:03:05.840
concentration of N2O5.

00:03:05.840 --> 00:03:07.860
And there's a constant
out here.

00:03:07.860 --> 00:03:08.900
The rate constant.

00:03:08.900 --> 00:03:11.390
So just to make the point, I'm
going to put a 1 here.

00:03:11.390 --> 00:03:14.150
Meaning that n equals 1 and
that's why this is a

00:03:14.150 --> 00:03:15.710
first-order reaction.

00:03:15.710 --> 00:03:16.680
But this is messy.

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:17.950
There's too many characters
here.

00:03:17.950 --> 00:03:21.270
So I'm going to compress this
and give myself a nicer font,

00:03:21.270 --> 00:03:29.110
so I'm going to let the
concentration of N2O5, just in

00:03:29.110 --> 00:03:30.850
this expression, just be c.

00:03:30.850 --> 00:03:31.700
Lowercase c.

00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:33.680
That way I can speed
this thing up.

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:38.490
So I can rewrite this expression
here as minus dc by

00:03:38.490 --> 00:03:42.850
dt equals k times c.

00:03:42.850 --> 00:03:43.540
All right.

00:03:43.540 --> 00:03:45.790
And so we know what this
is going to look like.

00:03:45.790 --> 00:03:47.980
They all look like this.

00:03:47.980 --> 00:03:51.630
If we plot concentration versus
temperature we expect

00:03:51.630 --> 00:03:54.540
to have the maximum value
of this at time zero.

00:03:54.540 --> 00:03:57.420
So at time zero I
start off with--

00:03:57.420 --> 00:04:00.120
if you want c-star or c max--

00:04:00.120 --> 00:04:02.900
and you know, this
thing attenuates.

00:04:02.900 --> 00:04:06.350
But I can't look at that and
decide whether it's first

00:04:06.350 --> 00:04:07.050
order or not.

00:04:07.050 --> 00:04:10.730
The only thing the eye
can really tell

00:04:10.730 --> 00:04:12.350
is a straight line.

00:04:12.350 --> 00:04:15.910
So what I want to do is I want
to modify this thing.

00:04:15.910 --> 00:04:19.500
I want to map c into
some f of c.

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:22.590
And I want to map t
into some g of t.

00:04:22.590 --> 00:04:28.490
So that if I plot f versus
g, I get a straight line.

00:04:28.490 --> 00:04:31.790
And then I can take one look at
that and go, bingo, this is

00:04:31.790 --> 00:04:32.690
first order.

00:04:32.690 --> 00:04:33.440
Or not.

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:36.880
Or maybe it's first order and
the data are very noisy.

00:04:36.880 --> 00:04:38.730
So what we'll do is
we're going to

00:04:38.730 --> 00:04:40.190
integrate that equation.

00:04:40.190 --> 00:04:42.760
So I'm going to play with
this a little bit.

00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:44.340
So I'm going to transpose.

00:04:44.340 --> 00:04:50.630
I'll get minus dc over
c equals kdt.

00:04:50.630 --> 00:04:57.830
And then I can integrate this
because I know at time 0, t

00:04:57.830 --> 00:05:00.550
equals 0, c equals
some value--

00:05:00.550 --> 00:05:03.450
I can call it c-star
or c naught--

00:05:03.450 --> 00:05:08.360
and at any arbitrary time later,
I can go down that

00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:12.180
curve and put some value of time
and then I'll end up with

00:05:12.180 --> 00:05:16.300
some arbitrary value
of concentration c.

00:05:16.300 --> 00:05:18.340
And I know there's some math
people in the audience who are

00:05:18.340 --> 00:05:22.500
probably horrified that the
limits and the integrand are

00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:23.540
both the same.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:25.370
So I'll put a little tilde
here that way I

00:05:25.370 --> 00:05:26.790
don't go to math jail.

00:05:26.790 --> 00:05:28.820
So now I'm not integrating c.

00:05:28.820 --> 00:05:32.460
If I wanted to be a pedant and
really make the math instead

00:05:32.460 --> 00:05:37.080
of me enslaving the math, the
math enslaving me, watch this.

00:05:37.080 --> 00:05:38.590
What I could do is I
could make this a

00:05:38.590 --> 00:05:40.480
carrier variable, s.

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:42.180
You know what I'm talking
about now, right?

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:43.700
But let's get really crazy.

00:05:43.700 --> 00:05:45.520
This is how bad the
math can get.

00:05:45.520 --> 00:05:47.070
You can do this in
a chemistry book.

00:05:47.070 --> 00:05:48.120
Let's use some Greek.

00:05:48.120 --> 00:05:51.080
So I'll make this
d xi over xi.

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:53.430
Now I've totally left the
class behind, but it's

00:05:53.430 --> 00:05:55.636
mathematically correct.

00:05:55.636 --> 00:05:58.170
What we will do is we'll
put the t back and put

00:05:58.170 --> 00:05:59.550
a tilde over it.

00:05:59.550 --> 00:06:02.950
And now everybody is happy, and
heaven forbid, the student

00:06:02.950 --> 00:06:07.140
might even understand
the lesson.

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:07.470
All right.

00:06:07.470 --> 00:06:09.120
So we do that and
what do we get?

00:06:09.120 --> 00:06:13.910
The integral of dc over c
is a natural log of c.

00:06:13.910 --> 00:06:17.810
This'll be natural log of c
equals natural log of c

00:06:17.810 --> 00:06:21.310
naught minus kt.

00:06:21.310 --> 00:06:24.870
OK, so integrating this thing
gives us this expression.

00:06:24.870 --> 00:06:31.870
And that means if I plot the
natural log of c versus time I

00:06:31.870 --> 00:06:33.910
should get a straight line.

00:06:33.910 --> 00:06:38.750
And furthermore, the slope
is equal to minus k.

00:06:38.750 --> 00:06:42.770
So here's an example that's
taken from your book.

00:06:42.770 --> 00:06:45.740
It happens to be another
first-order reaction and it

00:06:45.740 --> 00:06:48.850
shows the decomposition
of cisplatin.

00:06:48.850 --> 00:06:51.600
This is a compound that's used
in certain cancer treatments.

00:06:51.600 --> 00:06:54.040
And you can cisplatin hydrolyzes
to form this

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:56.540
monster cation plus
a chloride.

00:06:56.540 --> 00:07:00.160
And it turns out that the rate
of decomposition of cisplatin

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:01.030
is first order.

00:07:01.030 --> 00:07:02.530
Will you look at that curve?

00:07:02.530 --> 00:07:03.590
That purple line?

00:07:03.590 --> 00:07:04.635
I don't know what that means.

00:07:04.635 --> 00:07:05.790
But watch.

00:07:05.790 --> 00:07:10.040
If I instead plot the natural
logarithm of the concentration

00:07:10.040 --> 00:07:12.970
of cisplatin as a function of
time, you get a nice straight

00:07:12.970 --> 00:07:16.120
line, and furthermore,
the value of k is

00:07:16.120 --> 00:07:18.210
obvious from the slope.

00:07:18.210 --> 00:07:22.490
So this is an indication of the
power of taking the proper

00:07:22.490 --> 00:07:27.000
order of reaction and
then using it in--

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:30.290
if you'll pardon the pun--
straightening things out.

00:07:30.290 --> 00:07:32.920
And a couple other things
worth noting.

00:07:32.920 --> 00:07:35.830
I mentioned at the end of last
day, radioactive decay.

00:07:35.830 --> 00:07:40.440
Even though radioactive decay
is not a chemical reaction--

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:43.750
it has to do with nuclear
phenomena-- and we know

00:07:43.750 --> 00:07:46.910
chemistry is restricted to
the life and times of the

00:07:46.910 --> 00:07:49.080
electron, we don't go
into the nucleus.

00:07:49.080 --> 00:07:51.310
We simply know there's something
in there, there's

00:07:51.310 --> 00:07:54.150
neutrons, protons, and a whole
bunch of other particles.

00:07:54.150 --> 00:07:56.300
But chemistry is about
the life and

00:07:56.300 --> 00:07:58.200
times of the electron.

00:07:58.200 --> 00:08:02.590
Radioactive decay turns
out to be first order.

00:08:02.590 --> 00:08:05.370
It's good to know that
because then you can

00:08:05.370 --> 00:08:06.620
appreciate what goes on.

00:08:06.620 --> 00:08:09.040
So for example, you could
take something like the

00:08:09.040 --> 00:08:14.220
decomposition of uranium-238.

00:08:14.220 --> 00:08:17.260
One of its decompositions
gives you

00:08:17.260 --> 00:08:22.740
thorium-234 plus helium.

00:08:22.740 --> 00:08:26.140
And it turns out that this is
first order, which means that

00:08:26.140 --> 00:08:29.380
if you were to take a plot
of the natural log of the

00:08:29.380 --> 00:08:33.280
concentration of uranium
versus time, you get a

00:08:33.280 --> 00:08:34.220
straight line.

00:08:34.220 --> 00:08:37.030
And this slope would be the
k, the rate constant.

00:08:37.030 --> 00:08:40.980
But it turns out that the
nuclear chemists, nuclear

00:08:40.980 --> 00:08:46.040
engineers, prefer not to talk
about the rate of reaction in

00:08:46.040 --> 00:08:46.850
terms of k.

00:08:46.850 --> 00:08:49.710
But instead, they like to
use the inverse of k,

00:08:49.710 --> 00:08:51.640
which is the half-life.

00:08:51.640 --> 00:09:01.160
So instead, express k
through half-life.

00:09:01.160 --> 00:09:04.410
And the half-life, as the name
implies, is the time it takes

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:08.170
to decrease the concentration
of the species by half.

00:09:08.170 --> 00:09:14.080
So if I start off here at c1 and
down here I have c2 equals

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:19.780
1/2 c1, then this is the time
it takes to cut the

00:09:19.780 --> 00:09:22.160
concentration in half.

00:09:22.160 --> 00:09:24.410
So through half-life--

00:09:24.410 --> 00:09:29.040
and we can go through this
equation here, just put c

00:09:29.040 --> 00:09:33.650
naught over 2 and do a little
bit of manipulation, you'll

00:09:33.650 --> 00:09:37.670
end up with the natural log
of 2 divided by the rate

00:09:37.670 --> 00:09:43.140
constant, which is 0.693
divided by k.

00:09:43.140 --> 00:09:45.910
So you can see that there's
a direct relationship.

00:09:45.910 --> 00:09:49.650
It turns out that the half-life
for this reaction is

00:09:49.650 --> 00:09:52.960
4 1/2 billion years.

00:09:52.960 --> 00:09:55.130
4 1/2 billion years.

00:09:55.130 --> 00:09:58.090
So that means after 4 1/2
billion years the

00:09:58.090 --> 00:10:01.400
concentration has gone down to
a half, but even then it's

00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:03.420
probably not safe for the
kids to go out and play.

00:10:03.420 --> 00:10:05.690
So you really need to think
about it in this way.

00:10:05.690 --> 00:10:08.750
So here it is shown
in your textbook.

00:10:08.750 --> 00:10:12.220
Concentration as a
function of time.

00:10:12.220 --> 00:10:15.120
They could have plotted it log
linear, then you would have

00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:16.250
ended up with this.

00:10:16.250 --> 00:10:18.560
But anyways, they're chemists,
so what can you expect.

00:10:18.560 --> 00:10:19.190
So here it is.

00:10:19.190 --> 00:10:21.860
Here it goes down to a half, and
then this is a half of a

00:10:21.860 --> 00:10:22.750
half as a quarter.

00:10:22.750 --> 00:10:24.460
It's the same time interval.

00:10:24.460 --> 00:10:26.710
And then half of a quarter is
an eighth, and it's the same

00:10:26.710 --> 00:10:27.810
time interval.

00:10:27.810 --> 00:10:28.650
So you get the sense.

00:10:28.650 --> 00:10:31.630
And the most important thing
is the half-life is

00:10:31.630 --> 00:10:33.830
independent of concentration.

00:10:33.830 --> 00:10:36.070
It doesn't matter what the
starting concentration is-- if

00:10:36.070 --> 00:10:39.150
you know what the half-life is,
you know how much time it

00:10:39.150 --> 00:10:40.400
takes to get to a half.

00:10:40.400 --> 00:10:41.450
And you know enough math.

00:10:41.450 --> 00:10:43.560
What if I said, well, what if I
didn't want to go to a half?

00:10:43.560 --> 00:10:45.680
What if I wanted to go to 10%?

00:10:45.680 --> 00:10:49.380
Well, you can figure out how
to modulate half-life into

00:10:49.380 --> 00:10:50.310
tenth-life.

00:10:50.310 --> 00:10:52.150
That's trivial.

00:10:52.150 --> 00:10:55.280
But the book, being a chemistry
book, will show you

00:10:55.280 --> 00:11:00.180
a table in which they give
half-life values for orders of

00:11:00.180 --> 00:11:01.930
reactions other than 1.

00:11:01.930 --> 00:11:05.790
And it's stupid because except
in the case of first order

00:11:05.790 --> 00:11:08.960
reactions, the value the
half-life is a function of the

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:10.350
concentration.

00:11:10.350 --> 00:11:12.480
So what good is a constant
that's variable?

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:15.010
I don't know, but I didn't
write the book.

00:11:15.010 --> 00:11:18.080
The only time I care about
half-life is in the case of a

00:11:18.080 --> 00:11:21.620
first order reaction, which
is when you have

00:11:21.620 --> 00:11:23.970
nuclear decay for sure.

00:11:23.970 --> 00:11:24.360
All right.

00:11:24.360 --> 00:11:26.710
So that's enough about
first order.

00:11:26.710 --> 00:11:28.790
Let's go look at second-order
reactions.

00:11:28.790 --> 00:11:31.440
So here's an example also
taken from the book.

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:40.990
So second-order reaction, which
means that n equals 2 in

00:11:40.990 --> 00:11:42.670
the rate law expression.

00:11:42.670 --> 00:11:45.240
n equals 2 in the rate
law expression.

00:11:45.240 --> 00:11:49.460
And the example that
they gave was NO2.

00:11:49.460 --> 00:11:49.870
See, look.

00:11:49.870 --> 00:11:52.150
We went from N2O5 to NO2.

00:11:52.150 --> 00:11:54.600
And then we can keep the
decomposition going.

00:11:54.600 --> 00:12:03.100
NO2 goes to NO plus O2.

00:12:03.100 --> 00:12:06.070
And again, I'm going to let, in
this case, c will equal the

00:12:06.070 --> 00:12:09.450
concentration of NO2.

00:12:09.450 --> 00:12:13.120
And what you end up with in
this case is, if you go

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:16.610
through the similar analysis,
you get minus dc by dt.

00:12:16.610 --> 00:12:20.730
It's been measured that the rate
of loss of NO2 goes as

00:12:20.730 --> 00:12:23.040
the square of its
concentration.

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:26.350
So this is based on experimental
evidence.

00:12:26.350 --> 00:12:28.590
It's not because this is a 2.

00:12:28.590 --> 00:12:30.250
This is not.

00:12:30.250 --> 00:12:31.930
Please pay attention here.

00:12:31.930 --> 00:12:35.110
This 2 is not the consequences
of the stoichiometry.

00:12:35.110 --> 00:12:40.010
This 2 was determined
experimentally.

00:12:40.010 --> 00:12:41.950
I could have just written
this reaction NO2 goes

00:12:41.950 --> 00:12:43.305
to NO plus 1/2 O2.

00:12:43.305 --> 00:12:46.380
That doesn't make this
first order, does it?

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:51.300
Experimentally in
the laboratory.

00:12:51.300 --> 00:12:51.580
All right.

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:53.860
So now what we can do is we
can integrate this thing.

00:12:53.860 --> 00:12:57.156
And so we'll get minus the--

00:12:57.156 --> 00:12:59.460
let's do it this way.

00:12:59.460 --> 00:13:02.600
Boards are cheap, so let's jump
down to the next one.

00:13:02.600 --> 00:13:09.080
So now I can then put minus
the integral of dc tilde--

00:13:09.080 --> 00:13:10.080
cross multiply--

00:13:10.080 --> 00:13:17.050
so dc tilde over c tilde
squared equals k,

00:13:17.050 --> 00:13:19.230
the integral dt tilde.

00:13:19.230 --> 00:13:22.340
And we can integrate this from
zero to some time, and this

00:13:22.340 --> 00:13:25.750
will go from c naught to
some concentration.

00:13:25.750 --> 00:13:29.960
